entry.title: media/gpu/chromeos: Add base fixture class for PlatformVideoFramePoolTest
entry.content:
Previously, PlatformVideoFramePoolTest is a fixture class derived from

testing::TestWithParam, which is derived from both testing::Test and

testing::WithParamInterface [1]. However, this derivation declaration

prevents future test classes from extending their parameters when they

are subclass of the PlatformVideoFramePoolTest fixture class at the

same time in order to access the members within PlatformVideoFramePoolTest

class.



This CL proposes to add a base fixture class called

PlatformVideoFramePoolTestBase, which has all the original members and

the Initialization functions to keep the same functioning of the

PlatformVideoFramePoolTest. With this change,

PlatformVideoFramePoolTest is a subclass of this base fixture class and

the testing::WithParamInterface.



[1]

go/gunitadvanced#how-to-write-value-parameterized-tests

entry.title: Increase limit on interest groups per owner from 1000 to 2000.
entry.content:
This is a low-risk increase in the limit on the number of interest

groups per owner from 1000 to 2000. In practice, this limit is rarely if

ever reached. This change has been approved:

ChromeStatus feature: https://chromestatus.com/feature/6751281490427904

I2S: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/IfmYsMCUoHc/m/yCddTUfgBgAJ



Chromeâ€™s Protected Audience implementation limits the number of IGs that

one IG owner can place the user into. This limit originally served to

limit user device storage resource usage and user device compute

resources during auctions. We found better, more accurate, and less

biased ways to accomplish both of these goals without limiting the

number of IGs that one owner can place the user into, namely switching

to a size limit on all IGs and switching to a timeout on all IGs. This

change simply raises the limit on the number of IGs from 1000 to 2000.

entry.title: [Extensions] Don't pass in `valid_schemes` in script serialization
entry.content:
Currently, we pass in `valid_schemes` in script serialization, but this

always corresponds to the valid user script schemes according to

whether the extension can execute script everywhere. Since

`can_execute_script_everywhere` is *also* passed in, just use this

directly in `ParseMatchPatterns()`. This reduces code and, more

importantly, ensures the proper state of valid schemes and

`can_execute_script_everywhere` don't get out of sync.



This CL has no effective behavior change.

entry.title: Update It2Me host and friends to use a raw access_token
entry.content:
This CL adds a new kAccessToken message field which will be used to

provide a raw access token (i.e. not prefixed with `oauth2:`.

The impetus for this change is that today every caller which calls

into the CRD support host stack via Mojo needs to prefix their

access_token with 'oauth2:' which is error-prone and un-necessary.



Though this would typically be a straight-forward change, there are

two cases that need to be covered for compatibility:

1. The website changes are not in production yet so the It2Me NMH

needs to handle both old and new message fields for now

2. Lacros and Ash can have version skew so some translation is needed

to maintain compatibility.



#1 will be resolved prior to M121 branch point but #2 will require

that the shim code stick around until ~M124. I've added TODOs in the

relevant code blocks to remove the shims when it is safe to do so.



Please note that there are also changes needed in the remote_command

directory however the compat code I've added means that I can split

those out into a separate CL and have them approved by the OWNERs for

that directory.

entry.title: Announce match numbers in find bar results in screen readers.
entry.content:
Previously, when you would run find-in-page (ctrl-F),

on VoiceOver and NVDA the screen reader would announce

the results as you cycle through them ("Result 1 of 4",

"Result 2 of 4", and so on), but JAWS would not (it

was silent, giving no feedback that something happened),

and ChromeVox would not announce anything either (though

I think it reads the text of the match, which the

other screen readers don't do).



This CL fixes the issue with JAWS.



Note that ChromeVox's behavior is completely different (it reads

the full text of the item that matched the search phrase), and

this CL does not change that, which is intentional. It is unclear

if we want to change ChromeVox's behavior.

entry.title: IndexedDB: move some IDBFactory code to IndexedDBBucketContext
entry.content:
The `IndexedDBBucketContext` lifetime is somewhat complicated as

the object manages its own lifetime at times, but is also owned

by the `IndexedDBFactory`. This change is the first in a series

that attempts to simplify bucket context lifetime (creation,

initialization, deletion), which will be necessary in order to

draw clear lines between the bucket sequence and main IDB

sequence.



The specific change in this CL is to move management of the

bucket task queue into `IndexedDBBucketContext`, whereas

previously it was spread across `IndexedDBBucketContext` and

`IndexedDBFactory`. This code is relevant to bucket context

shutdown. There should be no functional change, just better

encapsulation. With this change, it is easier to imagine

`IndexedDBBucketContext` and `IndexedDBFactory` living on separate

threads, however there are also a lot of assumptions about

shutdown synchronicity which this does not resolve.

entry.content:
https://screenshot.googleplex.com/AoY7MajUCSjEAaK



Currently, the x-axis steps by 1. This makes it hard to see trends in

signals like `elapsedTimeLastVisitSecs` which often has values 100,000+.



So this CL increases the x-axis step for large signals:

- For signals within [0-99], the step remains 1

- For signals within [100-999], the step is 10

- For signals within [1000-9999], the step is 100

- etc



This CL also modifies the axis labels to avoid the labels overlapping

and becoming ineligible.



This CL also adds comma separators to the axis and plot-hover texts.
